%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:2/14/2011 12:32:28 PM
From:Jurgis Bekepuris
I don't incorporate cash in DCF or Buffettology calculations. The reason is
that both are looking at 10+ year results and it pretty much assumes that this
cash will be needed to achieve the results - whether for acquisitions or cap
investment, etc. You could make an argument that CSCO could distribute the cash
to shareholders right now and still produce the same cash flow / earnings
growth going forward. I disagree.

I went to http://trefis.com and played with their model. I am not affiliated
with Trefis, but I think they have pretty neat tool to play with (you may have
to register, free tool is available for limited set of companies, etc.)

 Note that they are using DCF, but they are predicting a "fair value" to which
the stock should rise based on their model. They are NOT doing the classical
DCF which gives you a price at which DCF would exceed the discount factor.
Their price ($24 in case of CSCO) is a TARGET price, classical DCF price is a
BUY price. Don't mix the two, the values they produce are not directly
comparable.

So I changed parameters in their model to yield the classical DCF results,
changed some values and got the price $16.37. This is classical DCF BUY price,
i.e. if you buy below $16.37, you will get ~15% return. I think even these
assumptions are a bit optimistic, but it jives well with my other calculations.
;)

Not sure if this link to my model will work, but I will post it anyway:
https://www.trefis.com/company?hm=CSCO.25081&shr=25081&from=share
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:2/14/2011 12:47:44 PM
From:Grantcw
Hello Jurgis,

Yes, your link works. Pretty neat application, I agree. I think that you and I
are on the same page with CSCO except that I'm factoring in CSCO's cash. If you
added $4-$7 in cash right now to $16.37, you'd be in my ballpark.

I understand your reasoning for not doing that, but my general reason for doing
so is to incorporate a balance sheet impact in my analysis. Two companies with
the same future cash flows should have different valuations if one has a great
balance sheet with a lot of cash, and the other doesn't.

But, everyone has their own analysis techniques. That's what I'm doing these
days. I will probably change to some degree down the road if/when I take a big
loss on something with a lot of cash! :) I appreciate the discussion...

Thanks,

Grant
