In examining this more, I think the difference in our perception of where CSCO
is cheap is that I'm not necessarily looking for a 15% return per year. When
I'm jumping into a large cap/low beta name like this, I'm really aiming at
somewhere between 11-15% per year, with the idea that:

1) If I'm buying Large Caps/Low Beta names, I'm probably looking towards a
correction and that this is a safer play than others.

2) If perception of CSCO is bad, I will monitor the stock price and take a
quick gain in some situations.

So, I think if you had my expectations and put your discount at 11%-12% instead
of 15%, CSCO might be cheap to you also. But, I understand trying to aim high
for 15% returns.

